   304	### D. Bare-repo bootstrap — one authoritative owner
   305	
   306	**Owner:** `setup-experiment.sh`. The repo is seeded **before**
   307	`docker compose up` runs, so the seed SHA is known synchronously and
   308	can be written into `.env` for downstream service flags.
   309	
   310	**Mechanism:** setup-experiment builds the shared image and then
   311	runs the one-shot init service (canonical command shape, matched
   312	in section E):
   313	
   314	```bash
   315	docker compose --env-file <generated-env> build eden-repo-init
   316	docker compose --env-file <generated-env> run --rm --no-deps eden-repo-init
   317	```
   318	
   319	against a new `eden-repo-init` service in `compose.yaml`. That
   320	service:
   321	
   322	1. `image:` references the same shared `eden-reference:dev` image
   323	   (so it has Python + the workspace + git available).
   324	2. Mounts only the `eden-bare-repo` named volume at
   325	   `/var/lib/eden/repo`.
   326	3. `command: ["python", "-m", "eden_service_common.repo_init",
   327	   "--repo-path", "/var/lib/eden/repo"]` — a new module that:
   328	   a. If `/var/lib/eden/repo/HEAD` already exists, prints
   329	      `EDEN_REPO_ALREADY_SEEDED sha=<existing-sha>` and exits 0.
   330	   b. Otherwise: runs `git init --bare
   331	      --initial-branch=main`, calls `seed_bare_repo`, prints
   332	      `EDEN_REPO_SEEDED sha=<hex>` to stdout, exits 0.
   333	
   334	The script captures stdout, parses the SHA, and writes it to `.env`
   335	as `EDEN_BASE_COMMIT_SHA=<hex>`. Then the operator runs `docker
   336	compose up`.
   337	
   338	**Crucially:** `eden-repo-init` is **NOT** in any other service's
   339	`depends_on`. It is a setup-time tool, invoked by setup-experiment
   340	via `compose run --rm --no-deps`, not a `compose up`-time
   341	dependency. This collapses the dual-owner contradiction codex
   342	flagged in plan-review round 0: setup-experiment is the sole owner
   343	of repo seeding, and
   344	the seed SHA is known *before* any service starts.
   345	
   346	The compose `profiles:` keyword keeps `eden-repo-init` out of plain
   347	`docker compose up`'s service set:
   348	
   349	```yaml
   350	eden-repo-init:
   351	  profiles: ["setup"]
   352	  ...
   353	```
   354	
   355	`compose run --rm <name>` runs services regardless of profile, so
   356	setup-experiment invokes it normally; plain `compose up` skips it.
   357	
   358	**Re-runnability:** `setup-experiment.sh` is idempotent. Running it
   359	a second time:
   360	
   361	- Re-runs `eden-repo-init`, which short-circuits on the existing
   362	  `HEAD` and re-prints the existing SHA.
   363	- Preserves existing secrets (postgres password, shared token) so
   364	  re-running doesn't rotate them by accident.
   365	- Overwrites `EDEN_PLAN_TASKS` and `experiment-config.yaml`.
   366	
   367	### E. setup-experiment script
   368	
   369	**File:** [`reference/scripts/setup-experiment/setup-experiment.sh`](../../reference/scripts/setup-experiment/setup-experiment.sh)
   370	(plus `README.md`).
   371	
   372	**Why bash, not Python:** the script's job is mostly to (a) read a
   373	YAML field from an existing config, (b) generate a `.env` file from
   374	a template, (c) print human-readable next steps. Bash is the
   375	simplest tool that fits, and it doesn't introduce a "you must `uv
   376	sync` before you can set up an experiment" bootstrap problem.
   377	Python would make the YAML read prettier (vs. `yq` or `python3 -c
   378	"import yaml; …"`), but trades it for the bootstrap requirement.
   379	The bash script will use a one-line `python3 -c` for YAML parsing
   380	since CI's runner has Python — that single dependency stays minor.
   381	
   382	**Inputs:**
   383	
   384	- Required positional arg: path to an experiment config YAML
   385	  (defaults to repo's fixture at
   386	  `tests/fixtures/experiment/.eden/config.yaml`).
   387	- `--experiment-id <id>` (default: derived from config filename
   388	  parent directory).
   389	- `--shared-token <T>` (default: a freshly generated 32-byte hex
   390	  string).
   391	- `--postgres-password <P>` (default: read from existing `.env` if
   392	  present, else freshly generated).
   393	
   394	**Outputs:**
   395	
   396	- `reference/compose/.env` (or `--env-file <path>`) — generated
   397	  Compose env. See section F for the full variable list.
   398	- `reference/compose/experiment-config.yaml` — copy of the input
   399	  config the task-store-server reads at boot via Compose `configs:`.
   400	- Stdout: a short "next steps" message — `docker compose up -d
   401	  --wait`. (**`up -d`, not `restart`** — `restart` does not pick
   402	  up changes to `command:`, env files, or `configs:`. `up -d`
   403	  detects config drift and recreates affected services. See
   404	  https://docs.docker.com/reference/cli/docker/compose/up/.)
   405	
   406	**Step ordering** (one-shot, synchronous, no chicken-and-egg):
   407	
   408	1. Generate / preserve secrets. Write a partial `.env` with
   409	   everything except `EDEN_BASE_COMMIT_SHA`.
   410	2. Copy the input config to `reference/compose/experiment-config.yaml`.
   411	3. `docker compose --env-file .env build eden-repo-init` so the
   412	   shared image is available before the next step runs. Build
   413	   output streams to stdout so the operator sees progress.
   414	4. `docker compose --env-file .env run --rm --no-deps eden-repo-init`,
   415	   capture stdout, parse the seed SHA.
   416	   - `--no-deps` keeps future dependency edits from accidentally
   417	     starting Postgres/Gitea/etc. just to seed a repo.
   418	   - The build in step 3 means this never fails on a missing image.
   419	5. Append `EDEN_BASE_COMMIT_SHA=<sha>` to `.env`.
   420	6. Print next-steps message.
   421	
   422	(`docker compose run --build --rm` would collapse 3+4 into one
   423	call, but the explicit two-step keeps build output and seed
   424	output cleanly separated in the operator's terminal — so a
   425	build failure is unambiguous and a seed failure is too.)
   426	
   427	### F. Compose dependency graph
   428	
   429	Final shape (post-setup-experiment):
   430	
   431	```
   432	postgres          → healthy (10a)
   433	gitea             → healthy (10a, idle this chunk)
   434	blob-init         → exited 0 (10a)
   435	eden-repo-init    → exited 0 (new; profile=setup, NOT in `compose up`)
   436	task-store-server → healthy [depends_on: postgres]
   437	orchestrator      → running [depends_on: task-store-server]
   438	planner-host      → running [depends_on: task-store-server]
   439	implementer-host  → running [depends_on: task-store-server]
   440	evaluator-host    → running [depends_on: task-store-server]
   441	web-ui            → healthy [depends_on: task-store-server]
   442	```
   443	
   444	`eden-repo-init` is invoked once by setup-experiment via
   445	`compose run --rm` *before* `compose up`; the bare-repo volume is
   446	already seeded by the time `compose up` starts the long-running
   447	services, so no `compose up`-time dependency on `eden-repo-init` is
   448	needed.
   449	
   450	Worker hosts and orchestrator are long-running clients without HTTP
   451	healthchecks; `compose up --wait` waits on `service_healthy` for
   452	healthcheck-declaring services and `service_started` for the
   453	others. Acceptable for this chunk.
   454	
   455	### F.1 Generated `.env` shape
   456	
   457	`reference/compose/.env` after a successful setup-experiment run:
   458	
   459	```dotenv
   460	# 10a (preserved or generated)
   461	POSTGRES_DB=eden
   462	POSTGRES_USER=eden
   463	POSTGRES_PASSWORD=<32-hex>
   464	POSTGRES_HOST_PORT=5433
   465	GITEA_SECRET_KEY=<64-hex>
   466	GITEA_INTERNAL_TOKEN=<64-hex>
   467	GITEA_HOST_PORT=3001
   468	GITEA_SSH_HOST_PORT=2222
   469	
   470	# 10b/c (new)
   471	EDEN_EXPERIMENT_ID=<from --experiment-id>
   472	EDEN_SHARED_TOKEN=<32-hex>
   473	EDEN_SESSION_SECRET=<32-hex>
   474	EDEN_STORE_URL=postgresql://eden:<password>@postgres:5432/eden
   475	EDEN_PLAN_TASKS=3
   476	EDEN_BASE_COMMIT_SHA=<seed-sha>
   477	WEB_UI_HOST_PORT=8090
   478	```
   479	
   480	### G. `compose-smoke` CI job extension
   481	
   482	The existing `compose-smoke` job (10a) already brings the stack up
   483	with `--wait` and asserts a few invariants. With 10b/10c added, it
   484	extends to:
   485	
   486	1. Run `bash reference/scripts/setup-experiment/setup-experiment.sh
   487	   tests/fixtures/experiment/.eden/config.yaml --experiment-id
   488	   smoke-exp` to generate `.env`. (This step also builds the image
   489	   and seeds the repo per section E.)
   490	2. **Assert seeded ref before starting the stack.** Reuse the
   491	   already-built `eden-reference:dev` image (it has git
   492	   installed) for a one-shot probe that mounts the volume:
   493	   `docker compose --env-file .env run --rm --no-deps
   494	   --entrypoint sh eden-repo-init -c "git -C /var/lib/eden/repo
   495	   show-ref refs/heads/main"` returns a SHA matching
   496	   `EDEN_BASE_COMMIT_SHA` from `.env`. Reusing the image
   497	   avoids depending on a floating `latest` tag of an external
   498	   image and matches the rest of the stack's pinning discipline.
   499	   This step also avoids races on long-running services that may
   500	   not yet exist or may have already exited.
   501	3. `docker compose --env-file .env up -d --wait --wait-timeout
   502	   180`.
   503	4. Existing volume + Postgres + Gitea assertions (10a).
   504	5. **New:** wait up to 60s for the orchestrator to exit 0 (the
   505	   scripted workers run a 3-trial experiment and the
   506	   orchestrator's `--max-quiescent-iterations` flag triggers
   507	   exit). The poll uses `docker compose ps -a --format json
   508	   orchestrator` and reads the exit code via `docker inspect
   509	   --format '{{.State.ExitCode}}' eden-orchestrator` (10a's
   510	   shape-stable pattern).
   511	6. **New:** assert the final task-store state — read `/v0/.../events`
   512	   over HTTP via `curl` + `jq` and confirm presence of a
   513	   `task.terminated` event for each plan task.
   514	
   515	Steps 5 + 6 turn the 10a smoke into a *light* end-to-end test —
   516	*not* the comprehensive 10e e2e (which adds Web UI walkthroughs,
   517	admin actions, and termination scenarios), but enough to catch a
   518	broken Compose wiring before merge. The tradeoff: smoke wallclock
   519	goes up from ~30s to ~90s. Acceptable.
